How biometry invaded our lives
Finish the password to tap to access his smartphone or pay for his purchases?
American, French or Japanese researchers predict a future where we will be recognized by biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, Deputy Director General of Morpho, even believes that "the century will be biometric."
Only biometry will ensure the identity of a person performing transactions in a world as transverse and transnational as the Internet.
The organizations dedicated to the protection of privacy confirm this commitment to biometry, but are concerned about it.
In 2011 and France, the National Commission for Computer Science and Freedoms authorized 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, the form of hand or the vinuous network of hand in companies, administrations, canteens...
"Everybody will soon be able to be identified, anywhere and whenever," said Justin Brookman, head of consumer privacy in the CDT (Centre for Democracy and Technology), Washington.
The reasons for such optimism in one another, and pessimism in the other?
Biometry will build on new technologies that will enable new services to be provided to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most used biometric data are fingerprints, hand contours and the venous network of palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its own constraints.
"For example, some people who work concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are illegible," says Philippe Robin, technical director of the field of identity at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection, as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand, involve a voluntary and specific gesture of the people.
This is both security - we cannot capture this data on their own - and a disadvantage: the procedure must sometimes be repeated and therefore takes time.
Consequently, research has been conducted for some twenty years on other approaches, such as facial or iris recognition (the colored part of the eye).
Thanks to increased sensor accuracy and computer computing capacity required for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has been multiplied by ten over the past five years, calculated Cyrille Bataller, Director of the Accenture R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the United Kingdom and Holland have deployed automatic border posts using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
"Today, we do research on the recognition of voice or how to walk with sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment," said Sridhar Iyengar, Director of Security Research at Intel Labs.
Unique and infallible marker, DNA also arouses hopes and concerns.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered as the ultimate biometric data," confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospective at CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers the judicial police services a bag of 90,000 euros to analyse DNA samples on the scene of a crime and in an hour.
Uses of biometry are divided into two groups: identification (recognizing one person among others) and authentication (ensure that the person is the person she claims to be).
The identification concerned the issue of identity papers so far: the biometric elements (prints, photos, iris) must be compared with the information that the state has on all citizens already set.
This makes it possible to ensure that a person does not attempt to usurp someone else's identity.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC thus offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or a store.
"We are recovering images from surveillance cameras and comparing them to photos of celebrities that move freely on the Internet," says Dany Nassif, responsible for commercial development at NEC France for biometric identification solutions.
Other use: take a picture of someone who tails in a store, follow his progression through facial recognition and calculate waiting time.
Authentication initially involved physical access (frontier, protected premises, canteens...) or logic (opening a computer).
In addition, more recently, the presence control was added.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the boyfriend who points for another," explains Cyrille Bataller, of Accenture.
But, increasingly, authentication will also concern transactions, in particular those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from certain distributors by introducing his card and placing his hand on a biometric drive: this gesture replaces the secret code hit.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by the Natural Security company in partnership with banks and major distribution teachers: at the time of paying in store with its bank card, the client does not type his code, but introduces his finger into a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is planned to last six months.
If successful, biometric readers could soon arrive at French merchants.
Paths to Secure Users
There are three ways of making biometry attractive to the eyes of the general public.
The first is to explain that she can make time.
"If, thanks to biometry, a client stays in caisse thirty seconds less, it's appreciated," says the director of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer tailor-made options.
And finally, make sure that the precautions taken to protect the databases are highlighted.
"The fingerprints are stored on a first server; the identities of the people are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure housing, which is blocked if you try to move it," says Philippe Robin, from Thales.
But, because of a lack of in-depth studies, it is impossible to know whether these speeches really convince users.
Privacy specialists continue to worry.
"The progress of facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, made me fear the worst: widespread surveillance," said Andrew Patrick of the Office of the Privacy Commissioner in Canada.
