Scientists have just highlighted the way a dog's tail movements are related to its mood.
Previous studies have revealed that the happy dogs raised their tails to the right (from the dog's point of view), while the nervous dogs moved it further to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trente, said: "Everyone knows that in humans, the left side and the right side of the brain are involved differently in stimuli that awaken positive or negative emotions."
Here, we tried to see what was in other species.
He added that as in humans, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to disordered tail movements of other dogs, researchers followed animals watching movies where other dogs were.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
It will probably not be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: "We presented to dogs the films where other dogs were - either a naturalist version or a silhouette to avoid any other confusion - and we were able to traffic the movement of the tail and present it as going more to the left or right."
When the animals saw a dog without expression stir the tail to the right (from the dog's point of view who pulled the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they found a tail drifting mainly to the left (again from the dog's point of view that pulls the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think the dogs would deliberately communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he thinks that dogs know by experience the movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: "If you meet other dogs several times and notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tails to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react to this experience."
Researchers indicate that results could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand their animals' emotions.
The canine behavior expert John Bradshaw, a guest professor at the University of Bristol School of Veterinary Sciences, explained that this was not the first study to examine the importance of the left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University discovered that the dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a joyful dog.
And in another scientific study carried out by Victoria University in Canada, he said: "The dogs went more easily to a robot dog when their tail was moving to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious - the opposite of what is in the Italian study."
He indicated that differences could arise from the fact that dogs who participated in the various studies did not fully regard the animals of the films or the robots dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs might be useful, he explained.
"Although many elements, recorded in different mammals, indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be specified – and dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviour can be recorded, it will certainly not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes moves on one side and sometimes on the other.
