A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society of New York identified a new species of hardwood dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, Scientific Mission Officer at the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Animals and Marine Milieux (OCEAMM) returns to L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Is the discovery of this new species of wooded dolphin surprising to you?
That's good news, but I'm not particularly surprised.
While in the past, species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis today, the development of new tools such as genetics enables us to improve our knowledge of species classification sciences.
Furthermore, it is not impossible for these advances in genetics and molecular biology to question the classification or membership of a species to a genus, a family, or even an order.
At the beginning of the 19th century, morphologists classified animals, based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these classifications are challenged because of the progress of genetics.
In the same way, two very morphologically close species were distinguished by genetics.
This is the case of the new species that has just been identified.
Ten years ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: the Pacific-Boss dolphins and the Atlantic-Boss whales.
Recent analyses have distinguished four species.
Why is this an important discovery as claimed by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences in order to protect the species and hence its genetic variability.
If this population had been known for a long time by the researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, only present at that place.
Therefore, if a problem of mass mortality caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture occurs in the region, we may have a case at the extinction of a species, rather than a local disappearance of a population of a more widespread species on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered threatened or endangered by the number of existing individuals on Earth, i.e. stock, and the possibility of recovery from neighbouring stocks.
As for the species Sousa chinensis, the population of the new discovered species, has been released, its stock has automatically become lower, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats, where there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This gene binding limits the creation of new species.
Conversely, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
We need to know that the marine environment is the least well-known environment.
We'd rather send robots to Mars than to know what lives in the Mariannes pit, just 11 kilometres from the surface of the sea.
